data.title: Arch Lifts
data.information: Arch Lifts increase resilience in the tendon in the arch of the foot. A sedentary lifestyle weakens your feet, which is why it’s important to train them in order to prevent injuries.

data.title: Arch of the Foot Ball Massage
data.information: Massage increases blood flow, which carries oxygen and nourishment to the area and stimulates healing.

data.title: Balancing Forward Bend
data.information: Balancing Forward Bend trains stability in your feet, ankles, thighs, buttocks, and back muscles, which improves their balance and control.

data.title: Ballerina
data.information: Ballerina improves flexibility in your big toe. Reduced big toe flexibility can cause pain in the arch of your foot, which is why it is important to restore and maintain good joint mobility in your big toe.

data.title: Big Toe Extension against a door frame
data.app_title: Big Toe Extension \nAgainst a Door Frame \n(2 sets)
data.information: Big Toe Extension against a door frame improves flexibility in your big toe. Reduced big toe flexibility can cause pain in the arch of your foot, which is why it is important to restore and maintain good joint mobility in your big toe. Big toe flexibility is also important for walking.

data.title: Destabilized Clock
data.information: Destabilized Clock trains your balance in different directions and improves stability in your feet and ankles, reducing the risk of injury. Standing on an unstable surface hones your balance even more.

data.title: Destabilized Stork
data.information: Destabilized Stork improves balance and stability in your feet and ankles. The unstable surface further increases difficulty, so make sure to perform the exercise near some form of support.

data.title: Diagonal Balancing Forward Bend
data.information: Diagonal Balancing Forward Bend trains stability in your feet, ankles, thighs, buttocks, and back muscles, which improves their balance and control.

data.title: Foot tilts
data.information: The purpose of Foot tilts is to maintain circulation in your ankles during prolonged inactivity. Challenging flexibility in different directions reduces the risk of stiffness.

data.title: Lateral Jump
data.information: Lateral Jump improves agility and resilience in your feet, ankles, heel tendons and calves, which allows for greater strain and reduces the risk of recurring injuries. Lateral jumps strengthen structures around the feet and knees.

data.title: Lateral Jump
data.information: Lateral Jump improves agility and resilience in your feet, ankles, heel tendons and calves, which allows for greater strain and reduces the risk of recurring injuries. Lateral jumps strengthen structures around the feet and knees.

data.title: Moving One-legged Jump
data.information: Moving One-legged Jump improves agility and resilience in your feet, ankles, heel tendons and calves, which allows for greater pressure on the area. It’s important to challenge your agility in a controlled setting before returning to sports or training that strains the injured area. Careful rehabilitation prevents recurring discomfort.

data.title: Rapid Lateral Jump
data.information: The purpose of Rapid Lateral Jump is to train agility and lateral stability, which is particularly important in order to prevent spraining your ankle again.

data.title: Seated Arch Stretch
data.information: Seated Arch Stretch stretches the tendon in the arch of your foot. Pain in the arch of the foot causes the tendon to contract and tighten. The stretch restores flexibility and prevents recurring discomfort.

data.title: Seated Foot Slide
data.information: The purpose of Seated Foot Slide is to maintain circulation despite deskbound inactivity and to reduce the risk of stiffness.

data.title: Sewing Machine
data.information: The purpose of Old Sewing Machine is to maintain circulation despite prolonged inactivity. Good circulation means a steady supply of oxygen and nourishment to the injured area, which creates an ideal healing environment and accelerates rehabilitation.

data.title: Single Leg Toe Lifts
data.information: Single Leg Toe Lifts strengthens your Achilles tendon and strains the arch of your foot, which increases resilience in the tendons of your heels and arches. Performing the exercise on one foot increases the strain, further improving resilience.

data.title: Single Leg Toe Lifts
data.information: Single Leg Toe Lifts strengthens your Achilles tendon and strains the arch of your foot, which increases resilience in the tendons of your heels and arches. Performing the exercise on one foot increases the strain, further improving resilience.

data.title: Square Jump
data.information: The purpose of Square Jump is to recover agility and challenge the stability of your ankles in different directions in order to improve functionality and prevent recurring discomfort.

data.title: Squeeze and Spread
data.information: The purpose of Squeeze and Spread is to maintain function and flexibility in the muscles that control your toes. This is particularly important if you have a hard time walking, and therefore don’t use the muscles in your feet like normal.

data.title: Standing Toe Piano
data.information: Standing Toe Piano strengthens your feet, improves resilience and reduces the risk of recurring discomfort. Performing the exercise standing increases the strain, which further strengthens your feet.

data.title: Stationary One-legged Jump
data.information: Stationary One-legged Jump improves agility and resilience in your feet, ankles, heel tendons and calves, which allows for greater strain and reduces the risk of recurring injuries.

data.title: Stork
data.information: Stork improves balance and increases stability in your feet and ankles. It’s important to challenge the limits of your balance in order for it to improve, so make sure to perform the exercise near some form of support.

data.title: The Clock
data.information: Clock trains your balance in different directions and improves stability in your feet and ankles, reducing the risk of injury.

data.title: Toe Lifts
data.information: Toe Lifts strengthen your Achilles tendon and strains the arch of your foot, which increases resilience in the tendons of your heels and arches.

data.title: Toe Lifts (2 sets)
data.information: Toe Lifts strengthen your Achilles tendon and strains the arch of your foot, which increases resilience in the tendons of your heels and arches.

data.title: Towel Roll
data.information: Towel Roll strengthens the muscles in your feet, increasing tolerance and resilience.
